'''Chan Kwok-Hung''' (陳國雄, c. 1963 – 17 December 2014) was a Hong Kong cinematographer. His credits, as director of photography or camera operator, included the 2000 action comedy ''[[Tokyo Raiders]]'' and the 2007 action drama ''[[Invisible Target]]''. He also received best cinematography nominations at the [[Hong Kong Film Awards]]  for ''[[Fly Me to Polaris]]'' in [[19th Hong Kong Film Awards|2000]] and ''[[Summer Holiday (2000 film)|Summer Holiday]]'' in [[20th Hong Kong Film Awards|2001]].<ref name="ST">{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/movies/story/cinematographer-jackie-chan-film-skiptrace-drowns-sampan-accident-hong-kong-2|title=Cinematographer for Jackie Chan film Skiptrace drowns in sampan accident in Hong Kong|work=The Straits Times|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>

Chan drowned when a motorised [[sampan]] he was in capsized in [[Ta Shui Wan|Sunny Bay]] off [[Lantau Island]] in [[Hong Kong]]. He and seven others (who all survived) were on a shoot for the [[Jackie Chan]] film ''[[Skiptrace (film)|Skiptrace]]''.<ref name="ST"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/entertainment/chan-kwok-hung-cinematographer-drowns-on-set-of-jackie-chan-film-1.2876087|title=Chan Kwok-Hung, cinematographer, drowns on set of Jackie Chan film|work=CBC News|date=17 December 2014|accessdate=17 December 2014}}</ref>

