In '''''Geldenhuys v Borman''''', an important case in the [[South Africa]]n [[inheritance|law of succession]], the [[testator]] had executed a total of three [[Will and testament|wills]], each revoking the previous one. For about three years the testator was a patient in [[Fort England Psychiatric Hospital|Fort England]], but he was released at a later stage. At the time the last will was executed, and although the testator was declared incapable of managing his affairs, there was no declaration that the testator was mentally incapable. Geldenhuys approached the court to declare all three wills invalid. The court noted that there is a [[informed consent#Competency of the patient|presumption of competency]], so that the onus of proof is on the person alleging [[Capacity (law)|incapacity]]. The court held that Geldenhuys had not discharged this onus, as incapacity to manage one’s affairs is not the same as mental incapacity. The wills were accordingly declared valid.
== See also == * [[South African law of succession]] * [[Geldenhuys v National Director of Public Prosecutions]]
== References == * ''Geldenhuys v Borman NO and Others'' 1990 (1) SA 161 (E).
