{{SouthAfrica-case-law-stub}}

The cells that give rise to the [[gametes]] are often set aside during [[Cleavage (embryo)|embryonic cleavage]]. During development, these cells will differentiate into [[primordial germ cells]], migrate to the location of the gonad, and form the [[Germline|germ line]] of the animal.
==Creation of germ plasm and primordial germ cells== Cleavage in most animals segregates cells containing [[germ plasm]] from other cells. The germ plasm effectively turns off gene expression to render the genome of the cell inert. Cells expressing germ plasm become [[primordial germ cells]] (PGCs) which will then give rise to the [[gametes]]. The germ line development in mammals, on the other hand, occurs by induction and not by an endogenous germ plasm.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Germ plasm in fruit fly=== Germ plasm has been studied in detail in Drosophila. The posterior pole of the embryo contains necessary materials for the fertility of the fly. This cytoplasm, pole plasm, contains specialized materials called polar granules and the [[pole cell]]s are the precursors to primordial germ cells.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
Pole plasm is organized by and contains the proteins and mRNA of the posterior group genes (such as [[oskar]], [[nanos gene]], Tudor, vasa, and Valois). These genes play a role in germ line development to localize nanos mRNA to the posterior and localize germ cell determinants. Drosophila progeny with mutations in these genes fail to produce pole cells and are thus sterile, giving these mutations the name 'grandchildless'. The genes [[Oskar]], nanos and germ cell-less (gcl) have important roles. Oskar is sufficient to recruit the other genes to form functional germ plasm. Nanos is required to prevent mitosis and somatic differentiation and for the pole cells to migrate to function as PGCs (see next section). Gcl is necessary (but not sufficient) for pole cell formation. In addition to these genes, Pgc polar granule component blocks phosphorylation and consequently activation of RNA polymerase II and shuts down transcription.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Germ plasm in amphibians=== Similar germ plasm has been identified in Amphibians in the polar cytoplasm at the vegetal pole. This cytoplasm moves to the bottom of the blastocoel and eventually ends up as its own subset of endodermal cells. These cells eventually become PGCs. The presence of homologs of nanos and vasa also implicate this germ plasm as germ-determining.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
==Migration of primordial germ cells==
===Fruit flies=== The first phase of migration in Drosophila occurs when the pole cells move passively and infold into the midgut invagination. Active migration occurs through repellents and attractants. The expression of wunen in the endoderm repels the PGCs out. The expression of columbus and hedgehog attracts the PGCs to the mesodermal precursors of the gonad. Nanos is required during migration. Regardless of PGC injection site, PGCs are able to correctly migrate to their target sites.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Zebrafish=== In zebrafish, the PGCs express two CXCR4 transmembrane receptor proteins. The signaling system involving this protein and its ligand, Sdf1, is necessary and sufficient to direct PGC migration in fish.
===Frogs=== In frogs, the PGCs migrate along the mesentery to the gonadal mesoderm facilitated by orientated extracellular matrix with fibronectin. There is also evidence for the CXCR4/Sdf1 system in frogs.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Birds=== In birds, the PGCs arise from the epiblast and migrate to anteriorly of the primitive streak to the germinal ridge. From there, they use blood vessels to find their way to the gonad. It is possible that the CXCR4/Sdf1 system is used.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Mammals===
In the mouse, [[Germ cell|primordial germ cells (PGCs)]] arise in the posterior [[primitive streak]] of the embryo<ref name=pmid20027186>{{cite journal |vauthors=Richardson BE, Lehmann R |title=Mechanisms guiding primordial germ cell migration: strategies from different organisms |journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=37–49 |date=January 2010 |pmid=20027186 |doi=10.1038/nrm2815|pmc=4521894 }}</ref> and start to migrate around 6.25 days after conception. PGCs start to migrate to the embryonic [[endoderm]] and then to the [[hindgut]] and finally towards the future [[Gonadal ridge|genital ridges]] where the somatic gonadal precursors reside.<ref name=pmid20027186/><ref name=pmid24240231>{{cite journal |vauthors=Svingen T, Koopman P |title=Building the mammalian testis: origins, differentiation, and assembly of the component cell populations |journal=Genes & Development |volume=27 |issue=22 |pages=2409–26 |date=November 2013 |pmid=24240231 |doi=10.1101/gad.228080.113 |pmc=3841730}}</ref> This migration requires a series of attractant and repellent cues as well as a number of adhesion molecules such as [[CDH1 (gene)|E-cadherin]] and β1-Integrin to guide the migration of PGCs.<ref name=pmid20027186/> Around 10 days post conception; the PGCs occupy the genital ridge<ref name=pmid24240231/> where they begin to lose their motility and polarized shape.<ref name=pmid20027186/>
==Germ line development in mammals== Mammalian PGCs are specified by signalling between cells (induction), rather than by the segregation of germ plasm as the embryo divides.<ref name="Ewen-Campen">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ewen-Campen B, Schwager EE, Extavour CG |title=The molecular machinery of germ line specification |journal=Molecular Reproduction and Development |volume=77 |issue=1 |pages=3–18 |date=January 2010 |pmid=19790240 |doi=10.1002/mrd.21091}}</ref> In mice, PGCs originate from the proximal epiblast, close to the extra-embryonic ectoderm (ExE), of the post-implantation embryo as early as embryonic day 6.5.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Wilson MJ, Dobie RA |title=Human short-latency auditory responses obtained by cross-correlation |journal=Electroencephalography and Clinical Neurophysiology |volume=66 |issue=6 |pages=529–38 |date=June 1987 |pmid=2438119 |pmc=3896947 |doi=10.1016/0013-4694(87)90100-3}}</ref> By E7.5 a founding population of approximately 40 PGCs are generated in this region of the epiblast in the developing mouse embryo.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Chiquoine AD |title=The identification, origin, and migration of the primordial germ cells in the mouse embryo |journal=The Anatomical Record |volume=118 |issue=2 |pages=135–46 |date=February 1954 |pmid=13138919 |doi=10.1002/ar.1091180202}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ginsburg M, Snow MH, McLaren A |title=Primordial germ cells in the mouse embryo during gastrulation |journal=Development |volume=110 |issue=2 |pages=521–8 |date=October 1990 |pmid=2133553 |url=http://dev.biologists.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=2133553}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Lawson KA, Hage WJ |title=Clonal analysis of the origin of primordial germ cells in the mouse |journal=Ciba Foundation Symposium |volume=182 |issue= |pages=68–84; discussion 84–91 |year=1994 |pmid=7835158 |doi=10.1002/9780470514573.ch5 |series=Novartis Foundation Symposia |isbn=978-0-470-51457-3}}</ref> The epiblast, however, also give rise to somatic cell lineages that make up the embryo proper; including the endoderm, ectoderm and mesoderm.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lanner F |title=Lineage specification in the early mouse embryo |journal=Experimental Cell Research |volume=321 |issue=1 |pages=32–9 |date=February 2014 |pmid=24333597 |doi=10.1016/j.yexcr.2013.12.004}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Schrode N, Xenopoulos P, Piliszek A, Frankenberg S, Plusa B, Hadjantonakis AK |title=Anatomy of a blastocyst: cell behaviors driving cell fate choice and morphogenesis in the early mouse embryo |journal=Genesis |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=219–33 |date=April 2013 |pmid=23349011 |pmc=3633705 |doi=10.1002/dvg.22368}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Gilbert |first=Scott F. |year=2013 |title=Developmental biology |edition=10th |publisher=Sinauer Associates |location=Sunderland |isbn=978-1-60535-173-5}}{{page needed|date=April 2014}}</ref> The specification of primordial germ cells in mammals is mainly attributed to the downstream functions of two signaling pathways; the BMP signaling pathway and the canonical WNT/β-catenin pathway.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Magnúsdóttir E, Surani MA |title=How to make a primordial germ cell |journal=Development |volume=141 |issue=2 |pages=245–52 |date=January 2014 |pmid=24381195 |doi=10.1242/dev.098269|pmc=3896947 }}</ref>
[[BMP4|Bone morphogenetic protein 4 (BMP4)]] is released by the extra-embryonic ectoderm (ExE) at embryonic day 5.5 to 5.75 directly adjacent to the [[epiblast]]<ref name="Ewen-Campen"/> and causes the region of the epiblast nearest to the ExE to express [[PRDM1|Blimp1]] and Prdm4 in a dose-dependent manner.<ref name="Saitou">{{cite journal |vauthors=Saitou M, Yamaji M |title=Primordial germ cells in mice |journal=Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Biology |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages= a008375|date=November 2012 |pmid=23125014 |doi=10.1101/cshperspect.a008375|pmc=3536339}}</ref> This is evident as the number of PGCs forming in the epiblast decreases in proportion to the loss of BMP4 alleles.<ref name=pmid10049358>{{cite journal |vauthors=Lawson KA, Dunn NR, Roelen BA, etal |title=Bmp4 is required for the generation of primordial germ cells in the mouse embryo |journal=Genes & Development |volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=424–36 |date=February 1999 |pmid=10049358 |pmc=316469 |url=http://www.genesdev.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=10049358 |doi=10.1101/gad.13.4.424}}</ref> BMP4 acts through its downstream intercellular transcription factors SMAD1 and SMAD5.<ref name=pmid10049358/><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hayashi K, Kobayashi T, Umino T, Goitsuka R, Matsui Y, Kitamura D |title=SMAD1 signaling is critical for initial commitment of germ cell lineage from mouse epiblast |journal=Mechanisms of Development |volume=118 |issue=1–2 |pages=99–109 |date=October 2002 |pmid=12351174 |doi=10.1016/S0925-4773(02)00237-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Tam PP, Snow MH |title=Proliferation and migration of primordial germ cells during compensatory growth in mouse embryos |journal=Journal of Embryology and Experimental Morphology |volume=64 |issue= |pages=133–47 |date=August 1981 |pmid=7310300 |url=http://dev.biologists.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=7310300}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ying Y, Zhao GQ |title=Cooperation of endoderm-derived BMP2 and extraembryonic ectoderm-derived BMP4 in primordial germ cell generation in the mouse |journal=Developmental Biology |volume=232 |issue=2 |pages=484–92 |date=April 2001 |pmid=11401407 |doi=10.1006/dbio.2001.0173}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ying Y, Liu XM, Marble A, Lawson KA, Zhao GQ |title=Requirement of Bmp8b for the generation of primordial germ cells in the mouse |journal=Molecular Endocrinology |volume=14 |issue=7 |pages=1053–63 |date=July 2000 |pmid=10894154 |doi=10.1210/mend.14.7.0479}}</ref> During approximately the same time, WNT3 starts to be expressed in the posterior visceral endoderm of the epiblast.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Liu P, Wakamiya M, Shea MJ, Albrecht U, Behringer RR, Bradley A |title=Requirement for Wnt3 in vertebrate axis formation |journal=Nature Genetics |volume=22 |issue=4 |pages=361–5 |date=August 1999 |pmid=10431240 |doi=10.1038/11932}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rivera-Pérez JA, Magnuson T |title=Primitive streak formation in mice is preceded by localized activation of Brachyury and Wnt3 |journal=Developmental Biology |volume=288 |issue=2 |pages=363–71 |date=December 2005 |pmid=16289026 |doi=10.1016/j.ydbio.2005.09.012}}</ref> WNT3 signalling has been shown to be essential in order for the epiblast to acquire responsiveness to the BMP4 signal from the ExE.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=2013PLoSO...857428T |title=Dullard/Ctdnep1 Modulates WNT Signalling Activity for the Formation of Primordial Germ Cells in the Mouse Embryo |journal=PLoS ONE |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=57428 |last1=Tanaka |first1=Satomi S. |last2=Nakane |first2=Akihiro |last3=Yamaguchi |first3=Yasuka L. |last4=Terabayashi |first4=Takeshi |last5=Abe |first5=Takaya |last6=Nakao |first6=Kazuki |last7=Asashima |first7=Makoto |last8=Steiner |first8=Kirsten A. |last9=Tam |first9=Patrick P. L. |last10=Nishinakamura |first10=Ryuichi |year=2013 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0057428 |pmid=23469192 |pmc=3587611}}</ref> WNT3 mutants fail to establish a primordial germ cell population, but this can be restored with exogenous WNT activity.<ref name=pmid24331926>{{cite journal |vauthors=Aramaki S, Hayashi K, Kurimoto K, etal |title=A mesodermal factor, T, specifies mouse germ cell fate by directly activating germline determinants |journal=Developmental Cell |volume=27 |issue=5 |pages=516–29 |date=December 2013 |pmid=24331926 |doi=10.1016/j.devcel.2013.11.001}}</ref> The WNT3/β-catenin signalling pathway is essential for the expression of the transcription factor T (Brachyury), a transcription factor that is was previously characterized somatic and mesoderm specific genes.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=1990Natur.343..617H |title=Cloning of the T gene required in mesoderm formation in the mouse |journal=Nature |volume=343 |issue=6259 |pages=617–22 |last1=Herrmann |first1=Bernhard G. |last2=Labeit |first2=Siegfried |last3=Poustka |first3=Annemarie |last4=King |first4=Thomas R. |last5=Lehrach |first5=Hans |year=1990 |doi=10.1038/343617a0 |pmid=2154694}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Naiche LA, Harrelson Z, Kelly RG, Papaioannou VE |title=T-box genes in vertebrate development |journal=Annual Review of Genetics |volume=39 |issue= |pages=219–39 |year=2005 |pmid=16285859 |doi=10.1146/annurev.genet.39.073003.105925}}</ref> T was recently found to be both necessary and sufficient to induce the expression of the known PGC specification genes Blimp1 and Prdm4.<ref name=pmid24331926/> The induction of Transcription Factor T was seen 12 hours after BMP/WNT signaling, as opposed to the 24 to 36 hours it took for Blimp1 and Prdm4 genes to be expressed. Transcription factor T acts upstream of BLIMP1 and PRDM4 in PGC specification by binding to the genes respective enhancer elements.<ref name=pmid24331926/> It is important to note that while T can activate the expression of Blimp1 and Prdm4 in the absence of both BMP4 and WNT3, pre-exposure of PGC progenitors to WNTs (without BMP4) prevents T from activating these genes.<ref name=pmid24331926/> Details on how BMP4 prevents T from inducing mesodermal genes, and only activate PGC specification genes, remain unclear.
Expression of Blimp1 is the earliest known marker of PGC specification.<ref name="Cinalli">{{cite journal |vauthors=Cinalli RM, Rangan P, Lehmann R |title=Germ cells are forever |journal=Cell |volume=132 |issue=4 |pages=559–62 |date=February 2008 |pmid=18295574 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2008.02.003}}</ref> A mutation in the Blimp1 gene results in the formation of PGC-like cells at embryonic day 8.5 that closely resemble their neighbouring somatic cells.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=2005Natur.436..207O |title=Blimp1 is a critical determinant of the germ cell lineage in mice |journal=Nature |volume=436 |issue=7048 |pages=207–13 |last1=Ohinata |first1=Yasuhide |last2=Payer |first2=Bernhard |last3=O'Carroll |first3=Dónal |last4=Ancelin |first4=Katia |last5=Ono |first5=Yukiko |last6=Sano |first6=Mitsue |last7=Barton |first7=Sheila C. |last8=Obukhanych |first8=Tetyana |last9=Nussenzweig |first9=Michel |last10=Tarakhovsky |first10=Alexander |last11=Saitou |first11=Mitinori |last12=Surani |first12=M. Azim |year=2005 |doi=10.1038/nature03813 |pmid=15937476}}</ref> A central role of Blimp 1 is the induction of Tcfap2c, a helix-span helix transcription factor.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Werling U, Schorle H |title=Transcription factor gene AP-2 gamma essential for early murine development |journal=Molecular and Cellular Biology |volume=22 |issue=9 |pages=3149–56 |date=May 2002 |pmid=11940672 |pmc=133770 |url=http://mcb.asm.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11940672 |doi=10.1128/mcb.22.9.3149-3156.2002}}</ref> Tcfap2c mutants exhibited an early loss of primordial germ cells.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Magnúsdóttir E, Dietmann S, Murakami K, etal |title=A tripartite transcription factor network regulates primordial germ cell specification in mice |journal=Nature Cell Biology |volume=15 |issue=8 |pages=905–15 |date=August 2013 |pmid=23851488 |pmc=3796875 |doi=10.1038/ncb2798}}</ref><ref name=pmid19776388>{{cite journal |vauthors=Weber S, Eckert D, Nettersheim D, etal |title=Critical function of AP-2 gamma/TCFAP2C in mouse embryonic germ cell maintenance |journal=Biology of Reproduction |volume=82 |issue=1 |pages=214–23 |date=January 2010 |pmid=19776388 |doi=10.1095/biolreprod.109.078717}}</ref> Tcfap2c is thought to repress somatic gene expression, including the mesodermal marker Hoxb1.<ref name=pmid19776388/> So, Blimp1, Tcfap2c and Prdm4 together are able to activate and repress the [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]] of all the necessary genes to regulate PGC specification.<ref name="Saitou"/> Mutation of Prdm4 results in the formation of PGCs that are lost by embryonic day 11.5.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=2008Natur.452..877H |title=Chromatin dynamics during epigenetic reprogramming in the mouse germ line |journal=Nature |volume=452 |issue=7189 |pages=877–81 |last1=Hajkova |first1=Petra |last2=Ancelin |first2=Katia |last3=Waldmann |first3=Tanja |last4=Lacoste |first4=Nicolas |last5=Lange |first5=Ulrike C. |last6=Cesari |first6=Francesca |last7=Lee |first7=Caroline |last8=Almouzni |first8=Genevieve |last9=Schneider |first9=Robert |last10=Surani |first10=M. Azim |year=2008 |doi=10.1038/nature06714 |pmid=18354397 |pmc=3847605}}</ref> The loss of PGCs in the Prdm4 mutant is due to failure in global erasure of histone 3 methylation patterns.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=2010Sci...329...78H |title=Genome-Wide Reprogramming in the Mouse Germ Line Entails the Base Excision Repair Pathway |journal=Science |volume=329 |issue=5987 |pages=78–82 |last1=Hajkova |first1=Petra |last2=Jeffries |first2=Sean J. |last3=Lee |first3=Caroline |last4=Miller |first4=Nigel |last5=Jackson |first5=Stephen P. |last6=Surani |first6=M. Azim |year=2010 |doi=10.1126/science.1187945 |pmid=20595612 |pmc=3863715}}</ref> Blimp1 and Prdm4 also elicit another epigenetic event that causes global DNA demethylation.<ref>{{cite journal |bibcode=2013Sci...339..448H |title=Germline DNA Demethylation Dynamics and Imprint Erasure Through 5-Hydroxymethylcytosine |journal=Science |volume=339 |issue=6118 |pages=448–52 |last1=Hackett |first1=Jamie A. |last2=Sengupta |first2=Roopsha |last3=Zylicz |first3=Jan J. |last4=Murakami |first4=Kazuhiro |last5=Lee |first5=Caroline |last6=Down |first6=Thomas A. |last7=Surani |first7=M. Azim |year=2013 |doi=10.1126/science.1229277 |pmid=23223451|pmc=3847602 }}</ref>
Other notable genes positively regulated by Blimp1 and Prdm4 are: [[Sox2]], Nanos3, [[Homeobox protein NANOG|Nanog]], Stella and Fragilis.<ref name="Saitou"/> At the same time, Blimp1 and Prdm4 also repress the transcription of programs that drive somatic [[Cellular differentiation|differentiation]] by inhibiting transcription of the [[HOX genes|Hox family genes]].<ref name="Saitou"/> In this way, Blimp1 and Prdm4 drive PGC specification by promoting germ line development and potential [[Pluripotency#Pluripotency|pluripotency]] transcriptional programs while also keeping the cells from taking on a somatic fate.<ref name="Saitou"/>
==Generation of mammalian PGCs in vitro== With the vast knowledge about in-vivo PGC specification collected over the last few decades, several attempts to generate in-vitro PGCs from post-implantation epiblast were made. Various groups were able to successfully generate PGCs, cultured in the presences of BMP4 and various cytokines.<ref name="pmid10049358"/> The efficiency of this process was later enhanced by the addition of stem cell factor (SCF), epidermal growth factor (EGF), leukaemia inhibitory factor (LIF) and BMP8B.<ref name=pmid19410550>{{cite journal |vauthors=Ohinata Y, Ohta H, Shigeta M, Yamanaka K, Wakayama T, Saitou M |title=A signaling principle for the specification of the germ cell lineage in mice |journal=Cell |volume=137 |issue=3 |pages=571–84 |date=May 2009 |pmid=19410550 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2009.03.014}}</ref> PGCs generated using this method can be transplanted to give viable gametes and offspring in vivo.<ref name=pmid19410550/> PGCs can also be generated from naïve embryonic stem cells (ESCs) that are cultured for two days in the presence of FGF and Activin-A to adopt an epiblast-like state. These cells are then cultured with BMP4, BMP8B, EGF, LIF and SCF and various cytokines for four more days.<ref name=pmid21820164>{{cite journal |vauthors=Hayashi K, Ohta H, Kurimoto K, Aramaki S, Saitou M |title=Reconstitution of the mouse germ cell specification pathway in culture by pluripotent stem cells |journal=Cell |volume=146 |issue=4 |pages=519–32 |date=August 2011 |pmid=21820164 |doi=10.1016/j.cell.2011.06.052}}</ref> These in-vitro generated PGCs can also develop into viable gametes and offspring.<ref name=pmid21820164/>
==Differentiation of primordial germ cells== Prior to their occupation of the genital ridge, there is no known difference between XX and XY PGCs.<ref name=pmid20027186/> However, once migration is complete, male and female PGCs begin to differentiate differently.
===Early male differentiation===
Male PGCs become known as [[gonocytes]] once they cease migration and undergo mitosis.<ref name=pmid23843237>{{cite journal |author=Culty M |title=Gonocytes, from the fifties to the present: is there a reason to change the name? |journal=Biology of Reproduction |volume=89 |issue=2 |pages=46 |date=August 2013 |pmid=23843237 |doi=10.1095/biolreprod.113.110544}}</ref> The term gonocyte is generally used to describe all stages post PGC until the gonocytes differentiate into spermatogonia.<ref name=pmid23843237/> Anatomically, gonocytes can be identified as large, euchromatic cells that often have two nucleoli in the nucleus.<ref name=pmid23843237/>
In the male genital ridge, transient [[Testis determining factor|Sry]] expression causes supporting cells to differentiate into [[Sertoli cells]] which then act as the organizing center for testis differentiation. Point mutations or deletions in the human or mouse [[Testis determining factor|Sry]] coding region can lead to female development in XY individuals.<ref name=pmid22964823>{{cite journal |vauthors=Sekido R, Lovell-Badge R |title=Genetic control of testis development |journal=Sexual Development |volume=7 |issue=1–3 |pages=21–32 |year=2013 |pmid=22964823 |doi=10.1159/000342221}}</ref> Sertoli cells also act to prevent gonocytes from differentiating prematurely.<ref name=pmid24324457>{{cite journal |vauthors=Rossi P, Dolci S |title=Paracrine Mechanisms Involved in the Control of Early Stages of Mammalian Spermatogenesis |journal=Frontiers in Endocrinology |volume=4 |issue= |pages=181 |year=2013 |pmid=24324457 |pmc=3840353 |doi=10.3389/fendo.2013.00181}}</ref> They produce the enzyme CYP26B1 to counteract surrounding [[retinoic acid]]. Retinoic acid acts as a signal to the gonocytes to enter [[meiosis]].<ref name=pmid24324457/> The gonocyte and Sertoli cells have been shown to form [[Gap junctions|gap and desmosomelike junctions]] as well as adherins junctions composed of [[cadherin]]s and [[connexin]]s.<ref name=pmid23843237/> To differentiate into spermatogonia, the gonocytes must lose their junctions to Sertoli cells and become migratory once again.<ref name=pmid23843237/> They migrate to the basement membrane of the seminiferous cord<ref name=pmid23843237/> and differentiate.
===Late differentiation===
In the gonads, the germ cells undergo either spermatogenesis or oogenesis depending on whether the sex is male or female respectively.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}
===Spermatogenesis=== {{Main|Spermatogenesis}} Mitotic germ stem cells, [[spermatogonia]], divide by mitosis to produce [[spermatocytes]] committed to meiosis. The spermatocytes divide by meiosis to form [[spermatids]]. The post-meiotic spermatids differentiate through [[spermiogenesis]] to become mature and functional [[spermatozoa]].{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} [[Spermatogenesis|Spermatogenic cells]] at different stages of development in the mouse have a frequency of [[mutation]] that is 5 to 10-fold lower than the mutation frequency in [[somatic cell]]s.<ref name="pmid9707592">{{cite journal |vauthors=Walter CA, Intano GW, McCarrey JR, McMahan CA, Walter RB |title=Mutation frequency declines during spermatogenesis in young mice but increases in old mice |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. |volume=95 |issue=17 |pages=10015–9 |year=1998 |pmid=9707592 |pmc=21453 |doi= 10.1073/pnas.95.17.10015|url=|bibcode=1998PNAS...9510015W }}</ref>
===Oogenesis=== {{Main|Oogenesis}} Mitotic germ stem cells, [[oogonia]], divide by mitosis to produce primary [[oocytes]] committed to meiosis. Unlike sperm production, oocyte production is not continuous. These primary oocytes begin meiosis but pause in [[diplotene]] of [[meiosis I]] while in the embryo. All of the oogonia and many primary oocytes die before birth. After puberty in primates, small groups of oocytes and follicles prepare for ovulation by advancing to metaphase II. Only after fertilization is meiosis completed. Meiosis is asymmetric producing polar bodies and oocytes with large amounts of material for embryonic development.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}} The mutation frequency of female mouse germ line cells, like male germ line cells, is also lower than that of somatic cells.<ref name="pmid23153565">{{cite journal |vauthors=Murphey P, McLean DJ, McMahan CA, Walter CA, McCarrey JR |title=Enhanced genetic integrity in mouse germ cells |journal=Biol. Reprod. |volume=88 |issue=1 |pages=6 |year=2013 |pmid=23153565 |pmc=4434944 |doi=10.1095/biolreprod.112.103481 |url=}}</ref> Low germ line mutation frequency appears to be due, in part, to elevated levels of [[DNA repair]] enzymes that remove potentially mutagenic [[DNA damage (naturally occurring)|DNA damage]]s. Enhanced genetic integrity may be a fundamental characteristic of germ line development.<ref name="pmid23153565" />
