{{Infobox State Representative | image = smkavulich.jpg | state_house = Pennsylvania | district = [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 114|114th]] | term_start = January 4, 2011 | term_end = October 16, 2018 | predecessor = [[James Wansacz]] | successor = TBD | birth_date = August 22, 1956 | birth_place = [[Taylor, Pennsylvania]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date and age|2018|10|16|1956|8|22}} | death_place = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S. | party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] | alma_mater = [[Williamsport Area Community College]] | occupation = Radio and television broadcaster | spouse = Linda Vass | children = 3 | residence = Taylor, Pennsylvania|, United States | religion = Roman Catholic | website = [http://www.pahouse.com/Kavulich/bio.asp Official Website] }} '''Michael G. Kavulich''' (August 22, 1956 – October 16, 2018), known as '''Sid Michaels Kavulich''', was an American politician, radio, and television broadcaster.
==Biography== Kavulich was born in [[Taylor, Pennsylvania]] and graduated from Riverside High School. In 1976, he received his associate arts degree in broadcasting from [[Williamsport Area Community College]]. Kavulich was a radio and television broadcaster.<ref>[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/MemBio.cfm?ID=1213&body=H Pennsylvania House of Representatives-Sid Michaels Kavulich]</ref>
==Political career== He was a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]]. He was first elected in [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives elections, 2010|2010]], and was sworn-in on January 4, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Scolforo|first=Mike|title=Pa. Legislature to Swear in Freshman Lawmakers Today|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/stories/local/state/pa-legislature-to-swear-in-freshmen-lawmakers-today-280339/?print=1|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref> He served on the Aging & Older Adult Services, Agriculture and Rural Affairs, Commerce, and the Finance Committees.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kavulich|first=Sid|title=State Representative Sid Michaels Kavulich's Home Page|url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/home/member_information/house_bio.cfm?id=1213|work=Pennsylvania Legislature|publisher=PA House of Representatives|accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref>
==Death== Kavulich died on October 16, 2018, at the University of Pennsylvania, in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, following complications from heart surgery.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lewis |first1=Ed |title=State Rep. Sid Michaels Kavulich, former sportscaster, died |url=https://www.timesleader.com/news/721672/state-rep-sid-michaels-kavulich-former-sportscaster-died |website=The Times Leader |publisher=The Times Leader |accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://www.citizensvoice.com/news/rep-sid-michaels-dies-1.2398135 Rep Sid Michaels dies]</ref> He was reelected unopposed on November 6, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/pennsylvania/articles/2018-11-13/cutler-chosen-to-succeed-reed-as-state-house-majority-leader|title = State House leadership elections bring change to Harrisburg |publisher = Associated Press |date = November 13, 2018 |accessdate = November 27, 2018}}</ref>
